	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Residual tariff barriers to ACP countries: Agricultural exports to the EU</h1>

			
			<h4>
												31 March 2005
										</h4>

					</header>


				<div class="intro">

						<p>
 <b>What residual tariff barriers exist?</b> <br />
 While the Cotonou Agreement allows duty-free access for the vast majority of ACP exports, this principle of duty-free access is qualified in sensitive sectors such as agriculture. Here, while special market-access arrangements exist residual tariff barriers also exist. The special ACP market-access arrangements are applied at two levels: for the ACP as a whole and for specific countries within the ACP. These special market-access arrangements are set out in annex V and Declaration XXII of the Cotonou Agreement and a series of commodity-specific protocols for sugar, beef and bananas. These establish various duty-free quotas, seasonal duties and import ‘ceilings’.<br /> </p>

		</div>
		
		
					<p> The residual tariff barriers faced by ACP exporters need to be seen against the background of two types of import duty applied by the EU in the agricultural sector: <i>ad valorem</i> duties and special duties. While products may enjoy a 100% reduction in the <i>ad valorem</i> duty, they may still be subjected to variable special duties. In the case of Declaration XXII, this means products may enjoy:</p>
<ul>

<li> full duty-free access (full exception from <i>ad valorem</i> duties and special duties); </li>

<li> quota-restricted <i>ad valorem</i> duty-free and special duty-free access; </li>

<li> quota-restricted <i>ad valorem</i> duty-free access and a partial reduction in the special duty; </li>

<li> quota-restricted reductions in the <i>ad valorem</i> and special duties; </li>

<li> seasonal quota-restricted <i>ad valorem</i> and special duty-free access; </li>

<li> seasonal quota-restricted <i>ad valorem</i> and special duty reductions.</li>

</ul>
<p> In all but the first of these categories residual tariff barriers exist. If agricultural products are not explicitly referred to in the list contained in Declaration XXII and no provisions is made for duty-free exports under other provisions (i.e. under the Protocols), then no preferential access is extended and residual tariff barriers also exist (see Annex 1 for a summary of the product coverage of Declaration XXII).</p><p> Perhaps the most visible residual tariff barrier under Declaration XXII is in the rice sector. Here quota-restricted access is allowed via two quotas:</p>
<ul>

<li> a quota of 125,000 tonnes for direct husked rice exports to the EU; </li>

<li> a quota of 20,000 tonnes for direct broken rice exports to the EU
<a href="#_edn1" target="_self">i</a>.</li>

</ul>
<p> On these quotas a 65% reduction in the duty charged is granted. ACP rice exported under these quotas pays only 35% of the standard import duty less €4.35 per tonne for husked rice and minus Euro 3.62 per tonne for broken rice. The actual duty applied varies on a fortnightly basis depending on the level of the reference price used. This costs Guyana and Surinam around €10 million per annum in import duties charged on rice exports ( Guyana €7 million, Surinam €3 million).</p><p> The removal of residual tariff barriers under declaration XXII and the protocols constitutes the principal tariff issue facing ACP non-LDCs under the EPA negotiations. Since these residual market-access restrictions do not apply to LDCs who will enjoy full duty- and quota-free access for originating products from 2008 onwards, this is not an issue for ACP LDCs.</p><p> In the case of the commodity-specific protocols, quota-restricted duty-free access is granted for sugar. In the case of beef, within the quota restrictions ACP exports still have to pay 8% of the special duty (that is to say they receive a 92% reduction in the special duty); this costs some £0.15 per kilo on exports to the UK.</p><p> In the case of sugar the residual tariff barrier issue is the removal of quantitative restrictions. In the case of beef the issue relates to the removal both of the quantitative restrictions on duty-free exports and the removal of the residual duty charged within quota.</p><table class="renderedtable" border="0" cellpadding="2" cellspacing="0" width="500">
<tr>
