</table>
<p> Source: Agronomic Board of Namibia</p><p> These grapes come on to the EU market shortly before Christmas and do not compete with any similar quality EU production. Despite the fact that total foreseeable Namibian production would scarcely impact on the EU market (equivalent as it is to around a single grape per EU citizen per annum) only a small tariff-free quota (800 tonnes) was granted. This is despite the large-scale employment and income gains (the industry currently employs 3,500 workers permanently and 7,000 part-time workers) which the removal of residual tariff barriers would generate in Namibia .</p><p> In October 2003 the EC took a proposal to the key EU trade committee, the so-called Article 133 Committee, to propose that upon entry into force of an EPA ACP countries should be granted access to the EU market equivalent to that accorded to LDCs under the EBA initiative. This indicates a willingness on the part of the EC to remove all residual tariff barriers to ACP exports, as part of the conclusion of the EPA negotiations
<a href="#1" target="_self">1</a>.</p><p> This is an important issue for Botswana , Namibia and Swaziland , which along with Lesotho find themselves <i>de facto</i> part of an economic partnership agreement with the EU, as a result of the application of the EU-South Africa Trade, Development and Co-operation Agreement to the whole territory of the Southern African Customs Union. In this context Namibian private-sector associations have called for the immediate introduction of full duty-free access for all originating Botswanan, Namibian and Swazi exports to the EU, in line with EC proposals to the Article 133 Committee in October 2003.</p><table class="renderedtable" border="1" cellpadding="2" cellspacing="0">
<tr>
<td width="614" valign="top">  <p><b>What can be done on residual tariff barriers under the </b><b>Cotonou</b><b> Agreement? </b> </p><p> Annex V, Chapter 1, article 1 (b) of the Cotonou Agreement allows for the inclusion of new agricultural products in the provisions of Declaration XXII. These provisions state</p><p> if during the application of this Annex, the ACP state request that new lines of agricultural production or agricultural products which are not the subject of specific arrangements when this annex enters into force should benefit from such arrangements, the Community shall examine these requests in consultation with the ACP states.</p><p> Notwithstanding the above the Community shall in the context of the special relations and special nature of ACP-EC co-operation, examine on a case-by-case basis the requests from the ACP states for preferential access for their agricultural products to the Community market and shall notify its decision on those reasoned requests if possible within four months, and in any case not more than six months after the date of their submission
<a href="#_edn4" target="_self">iv</a> .</p><p> Concessions granted in this regard should take account of:</p><p> the possibilities offered by the off-season market
<a href="#_edn5" target="_self">v</a>.</p><p> Thus improvements in preferences grated under declaration XXII can be secured upon submission of a reasoned request from the ACP, subject to a case-by-case review by the EC.</p>
  </td>
</tr>

</table>
<p> For LDCs in Africa the major issue generating tariff barriers relates to the EU’s rules of origin. Under the EU’s recent review of its GSP arrangement (which will run from 2006-2018) an opportunity arose to address these rules-of-origin issues which restrict ACP LDC exports. However, the EC prefers concerted action in a G8 framework on this crucial issue.</p><table class="renderedtable" border="1" cellpadding="2" cellspacing="0">
<tr>
<td width="565" valign="top">  <p><b>What Commissioner Mandelson has called for on rules of origin </b> </p><p> ‘I want to see origin rules designed as a way to help development, not impede it. I am for simplification and harmonisation of the rules so that ultimately the same rules apply in all markets and they are easy to use. I want Europe to bring forward proposals for new rules by the time of the Gleneagles G8 Summit. And I want the neglected WTO work on global harmonisation of origin rules also to pick up speed.’</p><p> Source: Speech by Commissioner Mandelson ( London School of Economics, February 4 th 2005 )</p><p>

<a href="http://europa.eu.int/comm/commission_barroso/mandelson/speeches_articles/temp_mandels_speeches_en.cfm?temp=sppm013_en" target="_self">http://europa.eu.int/comm/commission_barroso/mandelson/speeches_articles...</a> <br /> </p>
  </td>
</tr>

</table>
<p>
<b>The scope for action on residual tariff barriers</b> <br />
 Actions in favour of the removal of residual tariff barriers on ACP exports to the EU can be taken at four levels: <br /> </p>
<ul>

<li> the immediate approval of all requests under Annex V, Chapter 1, Article 1 of the Cotonou Agreement, for an extension of full duty-free access for products falling under Declaration XXII; </li>

<li> the immediate adoption of the October 2003 Commission proposal to the Article 133 Committee, that upon entry into force of an EPA, ACP countries should be granted access to the EU market equivalent to that accorded to LDCs under the EBA initiative; </li>

<li> the immediate implementation of this commitment in the case of Botswana, Namibia and Swaziland, since as a result of their membership of the Southern African Customs Union Agreement and the conclusion of the EU-South Africa Trade, Development and Co-operation Agreement, these ACP countries are already <i>de facto</i> members of an EPA with the EU; </li>

<li> the adoption of steps by the EU to establish derogation and cumulation arrangements for LDCs consistent with the constraints facing the most least developed countries in developing value-added processing activities.</li>

</ul>
<p><b>Annex 1</b> </p><p>
<b>Product coverage of declaration XXII</b> <br />
 The preferential treatment extended to a range of ACP agricultural products set out in Declaration XXII, the ‘ Joint declaration concerning agricultural products referred to in Article 1(2) (a) of Annex V’, covers certain categories of the following:<br /> </p>
<ul>

<li> Live animals (01) </li>

<li> Meat and edible meat offal (02) </li>

<li> Fish, crustaceans, molluscs and other aquatic invertebrates (03) </li>

<li> Dairy products (0401-0406) </li>

<li> Bird eggs (0407-0408) </li>

<li> Natural honey (0409) </li>

<li> Turtle eggs and others not specified (0410) </li>

<li> Other animal products (05) </li>

<li> Live trees and plants (06) </li>

<li> Potatoes (0701) </li>

<li> Tomatoes (0702) </li>

<li> Onions, shallots, garlic, leeks etc - fresh &amp; chilled (0703) </li>

<li> Cabbages, cauliflowers or similar vegetables (0704) </li>

<li> Lettuces -fresh and chilled (0705) </li>

<li> Carrots, turnips, beetroot and similar edible roots (0706) </li>

<li> Cucumber and gherkins - fresh and chilled (0707) </li>

<li> Leguminous vegetables (0708) </li>

<li> Other vegetables -fresh &amp; chilled (0709) </li>

<li> Vegetables uncooked or cooked by steaming or boiling (0710) </li>

<li> Vegetables provisionally preserved (0711) </li>

<li> Dried vegetables (0712) </li>

<li> Dried leguminous vegetables (0713) </li>

<li> Manioc, arrowroot and similar roots and tubers (0714) </li>

<li> Coconuts, brazil and cashew nuts (0801) </li>

<li> Other nuts (0802) </li>

<li> Dates, figs, pineapples, avocados, guavas and mangoes (0804) </li>

<li> Citrus fruit - fresh or dried (0805) </li>

<li> Grapes (0806) </li>

<li> Melons (0807) </li>

<li> Apples, pears, quinces -fresh (0808) </li>

<li> Apricots, cherries, peaches, nectarines, plums (0809) </li>

<li> Strawberries, raspberries, blackberries, currants, gooseberries (0810) </li>

<li> Fruit and nuts falling under 0811 </li>

<li> Fruit and nuts provisionally preserved (0812) </li>

<li> Apricots, prunes and other dried fruit falling under 0813 </li>

<li> Peel of citrus &amp; other fruit - fresh frozen or dried (0814) </li>

<li> Coffee, tea and spices (09) </li>

<li> Cereals (1001-1005) </li>

<li> Rice (1006) </li>

<li> Sorghum (1007) </li>

